  1. Introduction:

Radio waves emitted from pulsars reach Earth after traveling long distances in space which is filled with free electrons. Pulsars are rare and powerful neuron stars that have unique radio wave emission patterns and are searched by observing periodic radio signals (National Radio Astronomy Observatory, 2018). They emit a wide range of frequencies, and the amount by which the electrons slow down the wave depends on the frequency.

Pulsars are researched for their abilities as probes of space-time, the interstellar medium, and states of matter. Finding genuine pulsar signals is difficult due to most detections being radio frequency interference (RFI) and noise (Lyon et. al., 2016). As such, we will be addressing this by creating a classification model to predict whether unknown data points are pulsars. Our data classification model for pulsars is significant as it could assist researchers in identifying previously undetected pulsars. Additionally, the pulsar classification model could also have practical applications, such as improving our ability to detect radio signals from space.

The dataset we are working with was collected by Lyon et. al., and contains thousands of RFI/noise and true pulsar emission examples, with the latter being the positive minority. The data analysis will focus on three out of the nine attributes in the data, specifically the mean and skewness of the integrated profile (GHz), and the factor variable, of whether it is a pulsar (=1) or not (=0). Using the KNN algorithm, our goal is to develop a classification model that can determine whether or not a particular point may be categorized as a pulsar. In our report, we will explain our methods where we randomly split the available data into training and testing sets, cross-validate to assess the models accuracy, and visualize the data.

  1. Data Exploration

2.1. Loading Data

First, we loaded the necessary libraries for data manipulation and analysis, which include the tidyverse and tidymodels packages. We then read the dataset (HTRU_2.csv) into R and performed initial data cleaning by renaming the columns to more descriptive names and converting the 'is_pulsar' variable into a factor data type.

Table 1 shows the untidy dataset loaded into a table. In the complete dataset, we have 17898 observations, with 9 columns total. The last column, is_pulsar, is a dummy variable factor where it is equal to 0 if a particular observation is determined to be not a pulsar, and it is equal to 1 if a particular observation is determined to be a pulsar. For this paper, we will be using is_pulsar as our class. Additionally, note that the remaining 8 columns have the mean, standard deviation, excess kurtosis, and skewness statistics for both the integrated profile, which shows the distinct identity of each individual pulsar and remains stable throughout time, and the DM SNR curve (Liu, 2017).

2.2 Describing and Visualizing the Entire Dataset

Looking at Table 2, we note that the target column has a mean value of 0.09, which leans closer to the minimum value of 0. This shows that in the data, there are more "false pulse stars" where the class is determined as 0, than actual stars. Additionally, we clearly see this data needs some scaling since the difference between values is noticeable, and will therefore negatively impact our classification model if left unaddressed.

In order to make sure our hypothesis of data being easily separable for the majority of features is true, we are going to create a pairplot between columns and check if we can visually make that separation. Thanks to pairplotting it's clear that our data seems to be split in two huge separated groups that can be easily differentiated by just looking at the graphic above. The attributes that are used in this data analyses were ones that showed a visual relationship.

  1. Methods and Results

3.1. Choosing Attributes for Solving Our Classification Problem:

In order to be able to create results that are easier to interpret, the limitations of being able to visually represent our data, and the visualization codes we have learned, we have chosen to use two attributes in classifying our target variable. Although this may sacrifice a bit of accuracy compared to using the full dataset, we believe that using the mean and skewness of the integrated pulsar profile is sufficient enough to create a fairly accurate classification model. We chose the mean and skewness of the integrated pulsar profile due to reasonings made in data exploration to support this theory.

Additionally, Figure #2 further supports that the mean and skewness of the integrated profile are sufficient in classifying an unknown observation as a pulsar or not due to the clear pattern displayed in observations that are pulsars, versus points that are not. This gives us confidence that we will be able to develop a KNN classification model to be able to predict the classes of unknown points. In particular, we see that a relatively low mean-to-skewness ratio is more likely to be pulsars. It is noted that generally non-pulsars have close to 0 skewness, and means greater than 75 GHz. Pulsars are found to have skewness that is greater than approximately 5 GHz, and lower means that are from the range of 0-75 units. Figure 2 shows a scatterplot graph of our selected subset of data that we will be using for our classification problem. Note that the x-axis is our first selected attribute, the mean of the integrated profile, and the y-axis is our second selected attribute, the skewness of the integrated profile. Additionally, note that the colour of the points displays the class of whether the observation is a pulsar (=1), or not a pulsar (=0).

3.3. Dataset Splitting:

To evaluate the performance of our classification model, we split the dataset into a training set (75% of the data) and a testing set (25% of the data). We used a random seed (set.seed(1)) to ensure the reproducibility of the data split.

Figure 3 shows a scatterplot graph of the training data which used 75% of the original data from pulsar data. Note that the x-axis is our first selected attribute, the mean of the integrated profile, and the y-axis is our second selected attribute, the soreness of the integrated profile. Additionally, note that the colour of the points displays the class of whether the observation is a pulsar (=1), or not a pulsar (=0).

#Split the dataset into training and testing sets:
set.seed(1)
data_split <- initial_split(pulsar_data, prop = 0.75, strata = is_pulsar)
train_data <- training(data_split)
test_data <- testing(data_split)

3.4. Model Selection and Specification:

We chose the KNN algorithm for our project because of its simplicity and effectiveness in dealing with classification problems. KNN is a non-parametric, lazy learning algorithm that can handle datasets with multiple classes and is particularly suitable for pulsar classification due to the distinct emission patterns of pulsars.

3.5. Workflow Creation and Recipe Definition:

We created a KNN classification model using the tidymodels package, specifying the 'rectangular' weight function and a tunable number of neighbors. We then defined a workflow that included the KNN model and a recipe for the data, using the mean and skewness of the integrated profile as predictor variables and 'is_pulsar' as the target variable.

3.6. Model Tuning and Cross-Validation:

To optimize the model's hyperparameters and prevent overfitting, we performed a 5-fold cross-validation using stratified sampling based on the 'is_pulsar' variable. We created a grid of potential neighbor values (1 to 30) and used the tune_grid function to find the optimal number of neighbors for our KNN model based on finding the k that gives the highest F-score, which balances precision and recall. The F-score measures the accuracy of a binary classification, where the accuracy is the number of correct predictions divided by the number of total predictions. As such, the higher the F-score is to the maximum about of 1, the more accurate the test is.

3.7. Model Fitting and Evaluation:

With the optimal number of neighbors determined, we updated our KNN model specification and workflow to include the best K value. We then fit the final model to the training data. We evaluated the performance of our KNN classification model on the test set using accuracy, recall, precision, and F1 score as performance metrics. These metrics are essential for understanding the model's effectiveness in classifying pulsars, taking into consideration both false positives and false negatives.

In [20]:
#Create a KNN classification model using tidymodels:

knn_spec <- nearest_neighbor(weight_func = "rectangular", neighbors = tune()) %>%
  set_engine("kknn") %>%
  set_mode("classification")

knn_workflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(knn_spec) %>%
  add_recipe(recipe(is_pulsar ~ mean_profile + skewness_profile, data = train_data))

#Perform cross-validation to determine the optimal number of neighbors:
set.seed(1)
knn_vfold <- vfold_cv(train_data, v = 5, strata = is_pulsar)

knn_grid <- tibble(neighbors = seq(1, 30))

knn_tuned <- tune_grid(
  knn_workflow,
  resamples = knn_vfold,
  grid = knn_grid,
  metrics = metric_set(accuracy, recall, precision, f_meas)
)
In [22]:
#Select the best KNN model based on the optimal number of neighbors:

best_k <- knn_tuned %>%
  select_best(metric = "f_meas")

knn_best_spec <- nearest_neighbor(weight_func = "rectangular", neighbors = best_k$neighbors) %>%
  set_engine("kknn") %>%
  set_mode("classification")

knn_final_workflow <- workflow() %>%
  add_model(knn_best_spec) %>%
  add_recipe(recipe(is_pulsar ~ mean_profile + skewness_profile, data = train_data))

knn_final_fit <- knn_final_workflow %>% fit(data = train_data)

Conclusion and Discussion:

Using the KNN algorithm, we find that, generally, non-pulsar stars skewness values are nearly 0 GHz and their means are greater than 75 GHz. Pulsar stars, meanwhile, are usually found to have a skewness greater than 5 GHz and means lower than 75 GHz. The accuracy of this model is ~97%, making it reliable enough to be used to help classify new possible pulsar stars. As it is now, the classification model can also help improve spatial radio signal detection, though it can of course be further optimized for even more reliable functions.

To further improve the model, it is important to find ways to address missing data points and outliers (perhaps omitting incomplete points or manually sorting special cases). Alternatively, we can use all of the attributes for building our model and sacrifice visualization feasibility, or determine if any attributes from the dataset may be better for classifying pulsars than the ones we used through using ggpairs and boxplots to explore the correlation between variables and the target variable (such as excess kurtosis of the integrated profile). Additionally, further data should be researched and gathered on other possible tell-tale signs of pulsars aside from finicky radio-wave frequencies to be able to produce a more accurate classification model. We had hoped to use the ggpairs function to determine if there were more optimal attributes to use instead of skewness and mean of the integrated profile, but due to issues on Jupyter, we were unable to do so. Issues on Jupyter also prevented us from plotting the relationship between skewness and mean of the integrated profile of the entire dataset which would have further supported our decision to use these attributes. Moreover, we would have preferred to add a KNN Classification model but were unable to because of the same issues.
